.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-feature-catalog/references/examples.md:48:The catalog groups a large MCP surface into category folders, each holding one file per feature. The root `feature-catalog.md` is the only navigation surface and owns the section order; the folder names do not encode ordering. Both the category folders and the per-feature files use bare descriptive kebab-case slugs with no numeric prefix.
.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-feature-catalog/references/examples.md:54:The root `feature-catalog.md` opens with frontmatter carrying `title`, `description`, `trigger_phrases`, `last_updated`, and a 4-part `version`, then a short H1 intro that names what the system does today:
.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-feature-catalog/references/examples.md:66:Inside each category section, every feature is an H3 entry that stays deliberately thin — a `#### Description`, a `#### Current Reality`, and a `#### Source Files` callout that links to the per-feature file rather than inlining the source tables:
.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-feature-catalog/references/examples.md:77:#### Source Files
.opencode/skills/sk-doc/create-feature-catalog/references/examples.md:82:The OVERVIEW section is where this catalog carries system-specific context (a command-surface contract table, coverage maps). That is fine — but note what it does *not* do: it never dumps exhaustive source-file tables or scenario matrices into the root. That depth lives one link away, in the per-feature file.
